               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-128" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-128" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-128" type="surname" value="LOVELESS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-128" type="given" value="JOHN HENRY"></interp>JOHN HENRY LOVELESS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an officer of the Customs. On the even<lb></lb>ing of the 27th of May I was in King William-street—I found the prisoner's hand in my pocket—I caught him by the hand, and missed my handker<lb></lb>cheif—I wished him to give me my handkerchief—I saw him pass it to ano<lb></lb>ther person—as soon as I saw the handkerchief passing from his to his com<lb></lb>panion, I dropped his hand to catch at the handkerchief, and he got away—I ran after him a short distance—I saw him caught—he was not out of my sight—he begged of me to let him go.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. NAYLOR</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were there not a great many per<lb></lb>sons there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not a great many at the that spot—I felt a hand in my pocket—I had that hand in my hand when I was looking at the handkerchief—when I let go the hand, the person went away, and I went after him, to the bottom of Miles's-lane—I saw him caught—I saw a great many passengers, but they did not attract my attention—I did not lose sight of him after I had hold of his hand</p>
